I see what you're getting at and I understand it, but the reading experience is directly influenced by the style choice of writing, and is much more than a format, otherwise anon wouldn't be rewriting the leaves of fall in its entirety. Greentext impacts not only the readability of a story, but also its overall feel, sentences are short and. In fact one could insinuate that writing in greentext is as much of a clear change as switching from third person to second person, even without changing the reader's point of view (which is common among greentexts).
In short, greentext itself radically alters the exposition of a story and thus the story itself, and it was never meant for anything longer than telling your buds how you got smashed that one time and tripped over your own dick.

Then, start by writing a synopsis. Just flat, bare bones, facts by the numbers shit.
Then turn that synopsis into a list, a story by bullet points. Each part of the story in turn, but again, nothing in depth.
Now, if any one of those stands out as interesting, extrapolate on that point alone. Don’t worry too much about the nitty gritty of before or after, just focus on what you want a scene to portray. Narrowing down the stuff you’re happy and/or excited to write can often overcome the cringe factor, and as you want to flesh out the story, you should learn to focus on completing the narrative instead of worrying too much.
